Similar problem to give a man a fish he can eat for a day.. Teach a man to fish he can eat for the rest of his life. I do not feel the need to continue to fish for someone else who has a fishing pole in one hand and a phone in another. When it comes to the car market I again agree with you when there is likely going to be a huge problem with loans, and credit cards. This is not just their fault though, it takes two to create a loan and I heavily disagree with their marketing and I disagree with their morality on providing loans. I also disagree with the people signing up just so that they can impress some people at a stop light they will never meet when there are better options. It goes back to educating people to not make these decisions.

@To Wo did not say I was voting but thank you anyway. I also did not generalize all working people, you have my perspective twisted entirely. I understand how you feel about the unhealthy mindset but unfortunately we can't tell someone what to do with their money that they received based on a agreed upon transaction by both parties. I did not call anybody lazy either, I just think they have the wrong mindset about the way the system works. I also do not think welfare programs are a bad thing for sure. When I gave an example of how you could make it in today's America I did include someone who may have a brand new phone and vehicle because you truly can not make it on minimum wage if you decide to sign a dotted line stating that you are purchasing something far out of your price range. As for your issue with getting sick and being out of luck, most workplaces that want to keep their employees have sick days in the form of points, that people often use when they don't want to come in then do not have any left for when they really need them. But let me ask you this, what do you think we should do to help people without taking from somebody else to do so? I vote we encourage a savings mindset over spending so that people can be prepared against the situations that involve losing their job, and to work on getting forward rather than working on how to stay stagnant while getting everything they want. I again ask, how would you like to help people that does not involve involuntarily using someone else's money?

@To Wo You are right in the fact that we do not deserve Bernie I will agree with you on that note. Maybe not in the same way you mean but I would never vote against my own interest to say in the very least. Bottom line is we are voting for which perspective in life we have and who fits that perspective. For instance, mine is investing in mutual funds and Roth IRAs. These get better interest (or rate of return as it is more well known as) when companies end the accounting year with a higher profit margin. This means that, at a 10% rate of return you can invest just 100 dollars a month from 20 to 65 and have 1.2 million in retirement. As a financial analyst it is weird to hear people think that they can't make it in America today. Central America's cost of living is only 29% of the cost of living for the same place in San Diego, Los Angeles, and so on. If you want to make minimum wage the rest of your life and have enough to live on plus go on vacations twice a year, move to central America, work at a Wal-Mart, make 1400 a month full time, take 600 away for rent plus utilities (less with a roommate) then take 300 away for food , 100 away for gas, save 200 for emergencies, (each month) save 200 for vacations (each month) which puts you at 2400 vacation money in a year.

I get your perspective though and you have your right to it, but please don't pretend like it is anyone else's fault that you are not willing to change your life style. We have the richest poor class in the history of the world and we need to stop marketing brand new phones and cars to people who can not afford them.
